Yes, you can use the `onContextMenu` event in React to detect when a user right-clicks on an element. You can then use the `e.preventDefault()` method to prevent the default context menu from appearing, and open the link in a new tab programmatically using `window.open(url, '_blank')`. Here's an example:

```jsx
import React from 'react';

function MyComponent() {

  const handleRightClick = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    window.open('https://www.example.com', '_blank');
  };

  return (
    <div onContextMenu={handleRightClick}>
      Right click me to open in a new tab
    </div>
  );
}

export default MyComponent;
``` 

In this example, when a user right-clicks on the `div`, it will prevent the default context menu from appearing and open a new tab with the URL `'https://www.example.com'`.

Please note that opening new tabs programmatically can be annoying for users, so use it responsibly and make sure it provides value to the user experience.

If you want to continue to have the default context menu but also add additional logic before the user goes to another page on right click, you can do so by combining the `onContextMenu` event with the default behavior and adding your custom logic. Here's an example:

```jsx
import React from 'react';

function MyComponent() {

  const handleRightClick = (e) => {
    // Add your custom logic here
    console.log('Right-clicked!');

    // Continue with the default behavior
    return true;
  };

  return (
    <div onContextMenu={handleRightClick}>
      Right click me to see console log
    </div>
  );
}

export default MyComponent;
```

In this example, when a user right-clicks on the `div`, the custom logic (e.g., a console log statement) will be executed before the default context menu appears. The context menu with options like 'Open link in new tab' will still be shown to the user, and they can proceed to open the link in a new tab as usual.

You can replace the `console.log` statement with any custom logic you want to execute before the user goes to another page.

One approach to log the user off when they navigate to another page (e.g., by opening a link in a new tab) is to have a mechanism in place that detects when the user navigates away from the current page. You can achieve this by adding an event listener to the `beforeunload` event, which is triggered just before the page is unloaded.

You can use the `beforeunload` event to warn the user or perform an action (such as logging them off) before they navigate away. Here's an example of how you could use this event in a React component:

```jsx
import React, { useEffect } from 'react';

function MyComponent() {

  useEffect(() => {
    const handleBeforeUnload = (e) => {
      // Perform logout logic here
      console.log('User is logging out...'); // You can replace this with actual logout logic
    };

    window.addEventListener('beforeunload', handleBeforeUnload);

    return () => {
      window.removeEventListener('beforeunload', handleBeforeUnload);
    };
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>
      Your content here
    </div>
  );
}

export default MyComponent;
```

In this example, when the user navigates away from the page (e.g., by opening a link in a new tab), the `handleBeforeUnload` function will be executed, and it can handle the logout logic. You can replace the `console.log` statement with your actual logout implementation.

Keep in mind that the `beforeunload` event can only be used to provide a warning message to the user and perform some actions before they leave the page. It cannot prevent the user from navigating away or opening links in a new tab completely, as this behavior is controlled by the browser.

To track if a user has opened a new tab with a specific URL in order to log them off, you can use the `localStorage` or `sessionStorage` API to store a flag when the user opens a new tab with the specified URL. You can then check this flag on subsequent page loads to determine if the user should be logged off.

Here's an example of how you could implement this in a React component:

```jsx
import React, { useEffect } from 'react';

function MyComponent() {

  useEffect(() => {
    const handleLinkClick = (e) => {
      if (e.target.nodeName === 'A' && e.target.href.includes('specific-url')) {
        localStorage.setItem('isLoggedOff', 'true');
        // Perform logout logic here
        console.log('User is logging out...');
      }
    };

    window.addEventListener('click', handleLinkClick);

    return () => {
      window.removeEventListener('click', handleLinkClick);
    };
  }, []);

  // Check if user is logged off
  useEffect(() => {
    const isLoggedOff = localStorage.getItem('isLoggedOff');
    if (isLoggedOff === 'true') {
      // Perform logout logic
      console.log('User is logged off');
    }
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>
      Your content here
    </div>
  );
}

export default MyComponent;
```

In this example, the code listens for click events on the window. When a user clicks on a link that contains `'specific-url'`, it sets a flag in the `localStorage` to indicate that the user should be logged off. The `useEffect` hook then checks this flag on subsequent page loads to log the user off accordingly.

Remember to adjust the condition and logic inside `handleLinkClick` function to suit your specific requirements for determining when the user should be logged off based on opening a new tab with a certain URL.

If you want to track if a user has opened a new tab with a specific URL and log them off using WebSocket, you can implement a solution that sends a message to the server when the user navigates to the specified URL. The server can then handle the logout operation based on this message.

Here's a high-level overview of how you could approach this:

1. Implement WebSocket communication between the client and server.
2. Detect when the user navigates to the specific URL and send a message to the server via WebSocket.
3. Have the server listen for the message and trigger the logout operation for the user.

Below is an example of how you might implement this in a React component:

```jsx
import React from 'react';

function MyComponent() {

  const handleLinkClick = (e) => {
    if (e.target.nodeName === 'A' && e.target.href.includes('specific-url')) {
      const ws = new WebSocket('wss://your-websocket-server-url');

      ws.onopen = () => {
        ws.send('User navigated to specific URL');
        ws.close();
      };

      // Perform logout logic here if needed
      console.log('User is logging out...');
    }
  };

  window.addEventListener('click', handleLinkClick);

  return (
    <div>
      Your content here
    </div>
  );
}

export default MyComponent;
```

In this example, when the user clicks on a link that contains `'specific-url'`, a WebSocket connection is established with the server. A message is sent to the server informing it that the user has navigated to the specific URL. The server can then handle the operation to log the user off based on this message.

Remember to adjust the WebSocket connection URL and server-side logic to fit your specific implementation requirements.

